}{\plain \fs24 \b Eminent Domain: Negative Off-Case Positions}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \b I. Consequential synthetic\par
}{\plain \fs24 \b A. Holdouts\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab Eminent domain is just since it{\u8217\'92}s the only way to solve the injustices created by holdouts. \softline
Holdouts create injustices in two ways: (1) They force firms or other individuals to pay more \softline
than the fair market value for a given piece of land by exploiting its importance to large-scale \softline
development projects. (2) They can often prevent others in a given neighborhood who would like \softline
to sell their property from doing so. Since most people don{\u8217\'92}t want to move into slums, selling \softline
one{\u8217\'92}s land to private redevelopment firms may be the only way for those living in slums to \softline
escape them. But if one person in a neighborhood refuses to sell, it becomes impossible for \softline
anyone else in the neighborhood to sell either, denying them a chance to escape poverty and thus \softline
failing to give them their due. This is an on-face reason to negate since acts that directly redress \softline
injustice can{\u8217\'92}t be unjust.}{\plain \fs24 \b \par
}{\plain \fs24 \b \par
