}{\plain \fs24 \b II. Non-consequential synthetic\par
}{\plain \fs24 \b A. Critical evaluation of rights\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab Eminent domain itself isn{\u8217\'92}t just or unjust since its validity is contingent on the validity of \softline
the prior distribution of rights. Eminent domain is just the transfer of property rights from one \softline
person to another; in other words, it revokes one rights claim in favor of another. Logically, this \softline
is unjust if and only if the original claim is just, since unjust claims shouldn{\u8217\'92}t be recognized in \softline
the first place. Thus, you negate since the fact that a property right is recognized in the status quo \softline
doesn{\u8217\'92}t make it just. Existing distributions of property can be the product of past injustices or \softline
can serve to entrench an unjust balance of social power. In such cases, rejecting eminent domain \softline
impedes the pursuit of justice. For instance, attempts to redistribute land to freed slaves after the \softline
Civil War were stymied by the claim that such action would violate existing property rights, \softline
ignoring the fact that the concentrations of land in the hands of white landowners were the \softline
product of centuries of oppression.}{\plain \fs24 \b \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab Even if eminent domain is often used in ways that deny legitimate rights claims, in such \softline
cases it{\u8217\'92}s not eminent domain itself that{\u8217\'92}s unjust but the way it{\u8217\'92}s used in those cases, just as the \softline
fact that the state has levied lots of unjust taxes doesn{\u8217\'92}t show that the use of the state{\u8217\'92}s power to \softline
tax is unjust.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab This is an on-face reason to negate since (a) it logically precludes the truth of the \softline
resolution and (b) it indicts the assumption behind the AC that the present distribution of rights \softline
is just.}{\plain \fs24 \b \par
}{\plain \fs24 \b \par
}{\plain \fs24 \b \par
}{\plain \fs24 \b \par
}{\plain \fs24 \b B. Consent\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab State powers can{\u8217\'92}t be unjust if they are consented to by the governed since powers given \softline
to the state voluntarily act as extensions of the natural rights of the people. John Simmons writes: \softline
{\u8220\'93}}{\plain \fs24 \ul All political authority is artificial...Governments have the right to limit our liberty...insofar as \softline
they have been granted these rights by us. }{\plain \fs12 \fs12 We, however, possess these rights naturally.}{\plain \fs24  }{\plain \fs24 \ul Governmental rights, are \softline
simply composed of the natural rights of those who becomes citizens, transferred to the \softline
government by some voluntary undertaking}{\plain \fs24 .{\u8221\'94} Thus, the use of eminent domain can{\u8217\'92}t be \softline
inherently unjust since it is just to the extent that the people consent to it. Further, since all \softline
democratic states have some form of eminent domain power, the power of eminent domain has \softline
empirically been consented to by the people.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab The fact that takings are coercive doesn{\u8217\'92}t mean they lack consent, just as we consent to \softline
tax policies or laws that are inherently coercive since they{\u8217\'92}re backed up by the threat of force.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \b \par
