}{\plain \fs24 \b C. MacIntyre\par
}{\plain \fs28 \fs28 \tab }{\plain \fs24 The topic makes a claim about the justice of eminent domain. Thus, before we can debate \softline
on a standards level, the aff has a prima facie burden to prove a particular conception of justice, \softline
since if we don{\u8217\'92}t know what justice is we can{\u8217\'92}t tell if eminent domain violates it. But Alasdair \softline
MacIntyre shows that this is impossible: }{\plain \fs24 {\u8220\'93}}{\plain \fs24 \ul An agent can only justify a particular judgment by \softline
referring to some universal rule from which it may be }{\plain \fs12 \fs12 logically }{\plain \fs24 \ul derived, and can only justify that rule \softline
in turn by deriving it from some more general rule }{\plain \fs12 \fs12 or principle}{\plain \fs24 ;}{\plain \fs24 \ul  but}{\plain \fs24  }{\plain \fs12 \fs12 on this view }{\plain \fs24 \ul since every chain of \softline
reasoning must be finite, such a process }{\plain \fs12 \fs12 of justificatory reasoning }{\plain \fs24 \ul must always terminate with the assertion of \softline
some rule }{\plain \fs12 \fs12 or principle }{\plain \fs24 \ul for which no further reason can be given}{\plain \fs28 \fs28 . }{\plain \fs12 \fs12 Each individual implicitly or explicitly has to adopt his or her own first \softline
principles on the basis of such a choice.  }{\plain \fs24 \ul The utterance of any universal principle is in the end an expression of the \softline
preferences }{\plain \fs12 \fs12 of an individual will }{\plain \fs24 \ul and}{\plain \fs12 \fs12  for that will its principles have and }{\plain \fs24 \ul can have only such authority as [one] }{\plain \fs12 \fs12 it }{\plain \fs24 \ul chooses to \softline
confer }{\plain \fs12 \fs12 up}{\plain \fs24 \ul on [it]}{\plain \fs28 \fs28  }{\plain \fs12 \fs12 them by adopting them}{\plain \fs28 \fs28 .}{\plain \fs24 {\u8221\'94} Thus, proving claims about justice is impossible. This is an on-face \softline
reason to negate since it logically precludes the truth of the resolution}{\plain \fs24 \b \par
