}{\plain \fs24 \b D. Wittgenstein\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab The resolution can never be true since concepts of justice don{\u8217\'92}t correspond to anything in \softline
the external world. Ludwig Wittgenstein writes: {\u8220\'93}}{\plain \fs12 \fs12 Now what I wish to contend is that, although all judgments of relative value can be shown to \softline
be mere statements of facts,}{\plain \fs12 \ul\fs12  }{\plain \fs24 \ul no statement of fact can ever be, or imply, a judgment of absolute value. }{\plain \fs12 \fs12 Let me explain this: \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \ul Suppose}{\plain \fs24  }{\plain \fs12 \fs12 one of }{\plain \fs24 \ul you were }{\plain \fs12 \fs12 an }{\plain \fs24 \ul omniscient}{\plain \fs24  }{\plain \fs12 \fs12 person }{\plain \fs24 \ul and}{\plain \fs12 \fs12  therefore }{\plain \fs24 \ul knew all the movements of all the bodies in the \softline
world }{\plain \fs12 \fs12 dead or alive }{\plain \fs24 \ul and}{\plain \fs12 \fs12  that he also knew }{\plain \fs24 \ul all the states of mind of all human beings that ever lived, and }{\plain \fs12 \fs12 suppose this man}{\plain \fs12 \ul\fs12  \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \ul wrote all [this]}{\plain \fs24  }{\plain \fs12 \fs12 he knew }{\plain \fs24 \ul in a big book, then this book would contain the whole description of the \softline
world; and [yet] }{\plain \fs12 \fs12 what I want to say is, that }{\plain \fs24 \ul this book would contain nothing that we would call and }{\plain \fs24 \i\ul ethical}{\plain \fs24 \ul  \softline
judgment or anything that would logically imply such a judgment}{\plain \fs24 .{\u8221\'94} Thus, the resolution can \softline
never be true since if concepts of justice lack reference it{\u8217\'92}s impossible for anything to violate \softline
them. This is an on-face reason to negate since it logically precludes the truth of the resolution.}{\plain \fs24 \b \par
