}{\plain \fs24 \b III. Analytic\par
}{\plain \fs24 \b A. Eminent domain incompatible with private enterprise\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab American Heritage defines {\u8220\'93}private enterprise{\u8221\'94} as {\u8220\'93}business activities unregulated by \softline
state ownership and control.{\u8221\'94} Thus, {\u8220\'93}the use of eminent domain to promote private enterprise is \softline
a contradiction in terms since eminent domain asserts state control over private firms, meaning \softline
both that private enterprise can never coexist with the use of eminent domain and that even if it \softline
could the use of eminent domain would always harm rather than promote it by making it less \softline
private.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab Two impacts: (1) You negate on a logical level since affirming affirms a contradiction. \softline
(2) If the use of eminent domain to promote private enterprise can{\u8217\'92}t exist, it can{\u8217\'92}t be unjust. Both \softline
these impacts are a priori since they make the truth of the resolution logically impossible.}{\plain \fs24 \b \par
