}{\plain \fs24 \b B. State not a moral agent\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab American Heritage defines {\u8220\'93}justice{\u8221\'94} as {\u8220\'93}conformity to moral rightness.{\u8221\'94} Since justice is a \softline
moral concept, state action can{\u8217\'92}t be just or unjust since moral evaluation of state action is \softline
impossible for two reasons: (1) Morality can only apply to persons since moral evaluation \softline
presupposes choice and intentionality. An avalanche that kills a bunch of people would be bad \softline
but we wouldn{\u8217\'92}t call it immoral since it didn{\u8217\'92}t choose to happen. The state is just an institutional \softline
tool for implementing the choices of particular persons, none of whom personally embody the \softline
state. State actions are thus predetermined by external factors and can{\u8217\'92}t be just or unjust. (2) \softline
Even the acts of particular policy-makers aren{\u8217\'92}t freely chosen, since (a) they{\u8217\'92}re bound by legal \softline
constraints and duties and (b) they lack meaningful autonomy in their role as policy-makers \softline
since they can be removed from office and replaced if they fail to satisfy the wants of their \softline
constituents, making them just another level of institutional mechanism.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab Thus, you negate since eminent domain as a category of state action can{\u8217\'92}t be labeled just \softline
or unjust. This is a priori since it makes the truth of the resolution logically impossible.}{\plain \fs24 \b \par
